{{Infobox settlement <!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions --> | name = Kiryat Luza | native_name = {{lang|ar|قرية لوزة}}{{•}}{{Hebrew|קרית לוזה}} | settlement_type = Village | image_skyline = File:Culture of The Samaritans on Mount Gerizim 03.jpg | imagesize = | image_caption = | image_flag = | image_shield = | shield_size = | shield_alt = | shield_link = | pushpin_map = Palestine | pushpin_map_caption = Location of Kiryat Luza | coordinates = {{coord|32.203399|N|35.270081|E|display=inline,title}} | subdivision_type1 = [[Governorates of the Palestinian National Authority|Governorate]] | subdivision_name1 = [[Nablus Governorate|Nablus]] | leader_title = | leader_name = | unit_pref = | area_total_dunam = | area_metro_km2 = | elevation_m = | population_total = | population_metro = | population_as_of = | population_density_km2 = | population_demonym = | timezone1 = | utc_offset1 = | timezone1_DST = |region = | utc_offset1_DST = | area_code = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Kiryat Luza''' ({{lang-he-n|קרית לוזה}}, {{lang-ar|قرية لوزة}}) is a [[Samaritans|Samaritan]] village on [[Mount Gerizim]] near [[Nablus]], [[West Bank]] under joint Israeli and Palestinian control.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barbati|first1=Gabrielle|title=Israeli Election Preview: The Samaritans, Caught Between Two Votes|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/israeli-election-preview-samaritans-caught-between-two-votes-1028684|accessdate=14 October 2014|publisher=International Business Times|date=January 21, 2013}}</ref> It is the last wholly Samaritan village, half of their population living there.<ref>Louis J. Salome, ''Violence, veils, and bloodlines: reporting from war zones,'' McFarland, , 2010 p.76.</ref> The village houses the museum of the Samaritans. Kiryat Luza is adjacent to the Israeli settlement of [[Har Bracha]]. Until the 1980s, most of the Samaritans resided in Nablus below Mount Gerizim. The Samaritans relocated to Kiryat Luza as a result of violence during the [[First Intifada]]. Consequently, all that remains of the Samaritan community in Nablus itself is an abandoned [[synagogue]]. The [[Israel Defense Forces]] maintains a presence in the area.<ref>http://edition.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/meast/10/08/samaritans/index.html?iref=allsearch</ref>
