ogos}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| 2007 | style="text-align:center;"| <small>Still active</small> | A literary magazine. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=SCRC/> | style="text-align:center;"| — |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''Manqué'' | style="text-align:center;"| 2004 | style="text-align:center;"| 2004 | Slogan was "the presence of absence." It had been previously published in an online edition only. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=SCRC/> | style="text-align:center;"| — |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''Rocket'' | style="text-align:center;"| 2010 | style="text-align:center;"| <small>Still active</small> | Rocket Magazine is the premiere art and fashion publication at The College of William and Mary. Founded by Justin Miller in 2011, the purpose of Rocket is to provide an outlet for student artistic expression primarily through art and design, fashion, photography, and feature. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Rocket| work = | publisher = DSpace | date = | url = http://rocketmagazinewm.tumblr.com/| doi = | accessdate = January 11, 2012}}</ref> | style="text-align:center;"| [http://www.wm.edu/offices/studentactivities/clubsandorganizations/directory/media/rocket.php] |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''William and Mary Review'' | style="text-align:center;"| 1962 | style="text-align:center;"| <small>Still active</small> | Formed by union of the Royalist (1937–1962) and Seminar (1956–1962). | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=SCRC/> | style="text-align:center;"| — |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''William & Mary Comix'' | style="text-align:center;"| 2007 | style="text-align:center;"| 2009 | A publication with small print volumes containing artwork and comics created by students at the College. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = William and Mary Comics| work = | publisher = | date = | url = http://wmcomix.wordpress.com/| doi = | accessdate = February 8, 2009}}</ref> | style="text-align:center;"| [http://wmcomix.wordpress.com/] |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''Winged Nation'' | style="text-align:center;"| 1993 | style="text-align:center;"| <small>Still active</small> | Winged Nation is a literary arts magazine publishing only student work which "seeks to showcase students' unique view of the world through art, literature, and design." | style="text-align:center;"|<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Winged Nation| work = | publisher = DSpace | date = | url = http://dspace.swem.wm.edu/dspace/handle/10288/460| doi = | accessdate = February 16, 2009}}</ref> | style="text-align:center;"| [http://web.wm.edu/so/wingednation/] |}
==Humor and satire== {| class="wikitable sortable" style="width:100%" |- ! style="width:10%;"| Name ! style="width:7%;"| Began ! style="width:7%;"| Ended ! style="width:66%;" class="unsortable"| Notes ! style="width:5%;" class="unsortable"| Reference ! style="width:5%;" class="unsortable"| Link |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''{{sort|Ha!|Ha!}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| 1994 | style="text-align:center;"| 1994 | style="text-align:center;"| <small>Information unavailable</small> | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=SCRC/> | style="text-align:center;"| — |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''{{sort|Owl|The Owl}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| 1854 | style="text-align:center;"| 1854 | One of the earliest recorded examples of satirical literature at the College. The premier issue is the only remaining copy in Swem Archives. It debuted during the height of the [[antebellum era|antebellum]] period with the country torn over the issue of states rights and slavery. ''The Owl'' addresses many issues that would be considered controversial today, such as race and gender. Other issues addressed that are still present were professors, administration, and Williamsburg citizens. There is no evidence of funding found for ''The Owl''. A theory on this is that ''The Owl'' was merely a joke amongst a group of students and they used their own money to pay to have it printed. Also there is no evidence to prove that multiple copies were produced and distributed. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=LCST>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Satirical Publications Throughout the Years at William and Mary | work = | publisher = | date = | url = http://lcst201.wikispaces.com/The+Owl%2C+The+Scalper%2C+The+Taverner%2C+Sleuth | doi = | accessdate = February 17, 2009}}</ref> | style="text-align:center;"| — |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''{{sort|Pillory|The Pillory}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| 1991 | style="text-align:center;"| 2013 | A satire magazine and only publishes one issue per semester. The magazine does not have any competitors per se, as it is not a news reporting magazine. It is well-known on the College of William & Mary's campus, however, that ''The Pillory'' and ''The Virginia Informer'' generally dislike one another. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref>[http://www.vainformer.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=6889&Itemid=1 ''The Virginia Informer'' online: Are we funny? We report, you decide]. Retrieved on April 25, 2008.</ref> | style="text-align:center;"| — |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''{{sort|Sleuth|Sleuth}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| 2000 | style="text-align:center;"| 2000 | Two issue satirical magazine for the months of October and November. It was in a [[newsletter]] format – one long sheet with several humorous stories. ''Sleuth'' contained only one small advertisement per issue, located in the bottom right-hand corner. They provided coupons for the campus coffee house The Daily Grind and Williamsburg pub The Green Leafe, two popular student hangouts. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=LCST/> | style="text-align:center;"| — |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''{{sort|Taverner|The Taverner}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| 1987 | style="text-align:center;"| 1988 | A bound pamphlet, was composed of humor articles and stories within each issue. It never tried to mock real newspapers, thus making it a "soft news" publication. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=LCST/> | style="text-align:center;"| — |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''The Botetourt Squat'' | style="text-align:center;"| 2011 | style="text-align:center;"| Still Active | A satirical newspaper that mocks and provides humorous insight into campus culture. Named for the Botetourt Complex, infamous Freshmen dorms on New Campus. The newspaper does not currently have any competitors, though it occasionally jokingly derides ''The Flat Hat'' on principle. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=LCST/> | style="text-align:center;"| — |}
==Special interest== {| class="wikitable sortable" style="width:100%" |- ! style="width:10%;"| Name ! style="width:7%;"| Began ! style="width:7%;"| Ended ! style="width:66%;" class="unsortable"| Notes ! style="width:5%;" class="unsortable"| Reference ! style="width:5%;" class="unsortable"| Link |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''{{sort|Calling Out|Calling Out}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| 2006 | style="text-align:center;"| 2006 | Publication of the Asian Student Council. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=SCRC/> | style="text-align:center;"| — |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''{{sort|Colonial Echo|Colonial Echo}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| 1899 | style="text-align:center;"| <small>Still active</small> | The yearbook of the College of William & Mary, created entirely by students. The yearbook has been published every year since its first issue. Issues are published during [[homecoming]] weekend of the following academic year and distributed to students without additional charge. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=CE>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Colonial Echo | work = | publisher = The College of William & Mary | date = | url = http://people.wm.edu/~colech/ | doi = | accessdate = February 8, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> | style="text-align:center;"| [http://www.e-yearbook.com/College_William_and_Mary_Colonial_Echo_Yearbook] |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''{{sort|From the Margin|From the Margin}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| 2005 | style="text-align:center;"| 2006 | A discourse on minority experience. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=SCRC/> | style="text-align:center;"| — |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''{{sort|Iskra|Iskra}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| 1967 | style="text-align:center;"| 1968 | An alternative title was ''Spark''. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=SCRC/> | style="text-align:center;"| — |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''{{sort|Lips|Lips: Expressions of Female Sexuality}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| 2007 | style="text-align:center;"| <small>Still active</small> | A 'zine that was created by four students as a Women's Studies project in the spring of 2007. The purpose of ''Lips'' is to provide a space for open and honest expressions of sexuality from the female perspective. Entries include poetry, prose, essays, short stories, artwork, and magazine clippings. ''Lips'' is released once a semester. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dspace.swem.wm.edu/dspace/handle/10288/412 |title=Lips: Expressions of Female Sexuality &#124; The W&M Digital Archive |publisher=Dspace.swem.wm.edu |date= |accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wmpeople.wm.edu/site/page/wmlips/home |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 28, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510175413/http://wmpeople.wm.edu/site/page/wmlips/home |archivedate=May 10, 2010 }}</ref> | style="text-align:center;"| — |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''{{sort|Namet and Taket|Namet and Taket}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| 1945 | style="text-align:center;"| 1945 | Weekly volume designations during July and August 1945. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=SCRC/> | style="text-align:center;"| — |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''{{sort|Progressive|The Progressive}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| 2004 | style="text-align:center;"| 2006 | A [[social liberalism|liberal]], [[Left-wing politics|leftist]], and/or [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] magazine, alternatively known as the William & Mary Progressive. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=SCRC/> | style="text-align:center;"| [http://web.wm.edu/so/progressive/?svr=www] |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''{{sort|Uhuru|Uhuru}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| 1976 | style="text-align:center;"| 1976 | One issue (?). Other information unavailable. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref name=SCRC/> | style="text-align:center;"| — |- | style="text-align:center;"| ''{{sort|William and Mary|William and Mary Alumni Magazine}}'' | style="text-align:center;"| ? | style="text-align:center;"| <small>Still active</small> | The official magazine for all alumni of the College. It is mailed quarterly – once during each new season. It updates the alumni on happenings at William & Mary as well as future events and plans. In the back of the magazine it lists notable achievements by certain alumni per each graduating year, as well as any alumni deaths that have occurred since the previous issue. | style="text-align:center;"|<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Alumni Magazine | work = | publisher = | date = | url = https://www.wmalumni.com/?magazine| doi = | accessdate = February 8, 2009}}</ref> | style="text-align:center;"| [https://www.wmalumni.com/?magazine] |}
