{{other uses}}
[[File:Bauer-Stalo.png|thumb|right|An illustration from [[John Bauer (illustrator)|John Bauer]]'s folktale ''Stalo and Kauras''.]]
In the folklore of the [[Sami people|Sami]], a '''Stallo''' (also '''Stallu''' or '''Stalo''') is a large human-like creature who likes to eat people and who therefore is usually in some form of hostilities with a human. Stallos are clumsy and stupid, and thus humans often gain the upper hand over them.<ref>{{cite book|pages=237|title=Fragments of Lappish mythology|author1=Lars Levi Laestadius |author2=Juha Pentikäinen |author3=K. Börje Vähämäki  |last-author-amp=yes |editor=Juha Pentikäinen|publisher=Aspasia Books|year=2002|isbn=9780968588192|others=K. Börje Vähämäki}}</ref> The [[Vindelfjällen Nature Reserve]] contains the remains of ancient, large building foundations, considered by the Sami to be the remains of Stallone dwellings. There is also a huge stone placed on some small pebbles on top near Lake Giengeljaure named stalostenen, which literally means stone Stallo. Legend dictates that a Stallo would have placed a stone here to prove his strength.

